House History

Current Prototype

Working prototype at: https://cwickham.github.io/or-house-history/

Idea: Combine some views over time with a way to look at an individual year. Allows a general overview while being able to dig into specific years.

Current problems:

  • Not dealing with split terms (currently the legislators sit on top of each other)
  • Only using sessions after 1937. Why? From 1937 we have both 60 desks and 60 district numbers, which makes identifying vacancies and split terms easy.
  • A little hard to select a particular year, and keep that selection while hovering over individual legislators.
  • Need better popup tooltips when hovering over the time series (e.g.on majority plot, should read something like: In 2009, Democrats were the majority party with a 10% lead.)

House in a particular session

Advantages:

  • Easily see which party has majority (e.g.do they travel over the 50% point), and a rough comparison of the proportion that are female.
  • Each square represents a desk, so can provide legislator information on demand.

Disadvantages:

  • Harder to deal with split terms (might visually split squares).
  • While the layout is reminiscent of the house floor it isnt exactly, and position doesnt directly correspond to desk location.
  • No way to easily find the history of a particular district/desk.

Majority party over time

Advantages:

  • Highlights the most important feature - who has the majority and by how much?
  • Bars also highlight the changing frequency of regular sessions.

Disadvantages:

  • Not clear how well this works prior to 1939 (Who is the minority party? What if no party has a majority?)
  • Party in power is only coded by color, which may make it harder for those without full color vision to distinguish.

Gender balance over time

Advantages:

  • Gives a good overview of trend over time for the whole house, as well as difference between two major parties.

Disadvantages:

  • Need to think about future non-binary legislators, would % not male be more useful?
  • Only shows two partiesother parties tend to be small so more variation in percentage (e.g.either 0% or 100%).

Alternatives

Using the same general structure could swap out these particular views for other ones.

House in a particular session

A barchart

Advantages:

  • Easy to see majority party
  • Possible to see rough proportion of a party that is female.

Disadvantages:

  • Hard to map to individual legislators
  • Hard to see overall gender breakdown

Side by side barcharts

Advantages:

  • Easy to see majority party
  • Possible to see rough proportion of a party that is female.

Disadvantages:

  • Hard to map to individual legislators
  • Hard to see overall gender breakdown

Semi-visual listing

Advantages:

  • Complete orderable listing of legislators makes it easy to look up a district, or see all names for a particular party/gender.

Disadvantages:

  • Takes up a lot of space, doesnt help with getting a quick idea of the breakdown by party or gender.

Additional session level info displayed visually

E.g. for 1999

Republican 34 seats 24% female
Democrat 25 seats 44% female
Independent 1 seats 0% female
